Part 3: Working with Categorical Variables¶

I will be creating lists to specify the order for each of the three categorical variables.

In [9]:
#Create three lists named representing the levels of the associated categorical variable from worst to best
clarity_levels = ['I1', 'SI2', 'SI1', 'VS2', 'VS1', 'VVS2', 'VVS1', 'IF']
cut_levels = ['Fair', 'Good', 'Very Good', 'Premium', 'Ideal']
color_levels = ['J', 'I', 'H', 'G', 'F', 'E', 'D']

I will use these lists to communicate to Pandas the correct order for the levels of the three categorical variables

In [10]:
# Use pd.Categorical() to set the levels of the cut, color, and clarity columns

diamonds.clarity = pd.Categorical(diamonds.clarity, clarity_levels)
diamonds.cut = pd.Categorical(diamonds.cut, cut_levels)
diamonds.color = pd.Categorical(diamonds.color, color_levels)

I will create lists of named colors to serve as palettes to be used for visualizations later in the notebook.

In [11]:
# Create three lists containing a number of named colors 
clarity_pal = ['red', 'orange', 'yellow', 'green', 'blue', 'indigo', 'darkviolet', 'magenta']
cut_pal = ['red','orange', 'yellow', 'green','blue']
color_pal = ['red','orange','yellow', 'green','blue','indigo','darkviolet']

Part 5: Scatterplots of Price Against Carat¶

In this part, I will explore the relationship between the price and carat attributes by generating scatter plots.

In [15]:
# Create a scatterplot of price against carat

plt.figure(figsize=[8,6])
plt.scatter(x=diamonds.carat, 
            y=diamonds.price, 
            s=20, 
            alpha=0.4,
            color='violet'
           )

plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Price (in $)')
plt.title('Relationship between Diamond Price and Carat Size')

plt.show()

I will reproduce the plot from above, but will now color the points according to their clarity.

In [16]:
# Create a scatterplot of price against carat with the point color indicating the clarity level

plt.figure(figsize=[8,6])

for i in range(0, len(clarity_levels)):
    plt.scatter(x=diamonds.carat[diamonds.clarity == clarity_levels[i]],
                y=diamonds.price[diamonds.clarity == clarity_levels[i]], 
                s=20, 
                alpha=0.4,
                label= clarity_levels[i],
                color= clarity_pal[i]
                )

plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Price (in $)')
plt.title('Relationship between Diamond Price and Carat Size')

plt.legend()
plt.show()

I will separate the points for each of the eight clarity levels into its own subplot.

In [17]:
# Create a scatterplot of price against carat with the point color indicating the clarity level on its own scatter plot

plt.figure(figsize=[12,6])

for i in range(0, len(clarity_levels)):
    plt.subplot(2,4,1+i)
    
    plt.scatter(x=diamonds.carat[diamonds.clarity == clarity_levels[i]],
                y=diamonds.price[diamonds.clarity == clarity_levels[i]], 
                s=20, 
                alpha=0.4,
                label= clarity_levels[i],
                color= clarity_pal[i]
                )
    
    plt.xlim([0, 4])
    plt.ylim([0, 20000])
    plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
    plt.ylabel('Price (in $)')
    plt.title(clarity_levels[i])

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Part 6: Applying Logarithmic Transformations¶

I will start by adding two new columns to the diamonds in order to store the transformed variables.

In [18]:
# add two columns named ln_carat and ln_price to diamonds with values of natural log of carat and price respectively

diamonds['ln_carat'] = np.log(diamonds['carat'])
diamonds['ln_price'] = np.log(diamonds['price'])

I will use histograms to explore the distribution of the diamond prices and the log of the diamond prices.

In [19]:
# display two side-by-side histograms
# histogram on the left should be for price and the one on the right should be for ln_price

plt.figure(figsize=[12,4])

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.hist(diamonds.price, edgecolor='k', color='dodgerblue', bins=20)
plt.title('Histogram of Prices')
plt.xlabel('Price')
plt.ylabel('Count')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.hist(diamonds.ln_price, edgecolor='k', color='palevioletred', bins=20)
plt.title('Histogram of Log-Prices')
plt.xlabel('Natural Log of Price')
plt.ylabel('Count')

plt.show()

I will now use histograms to explore the distribution of the carat sizes, and the log of the carat sizes.

In [20]:
# display two side-by-side histograms
# histogram on the left should be for price and the one on the right should be for ln_price

plt.figure(figsize=[12,4])

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.hist(diamonds.carat, edgecolor='k', color='lightgreen', bins=20)
plt.title('Histogram of Carat Sizes')
plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Count')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.hist(diamonds.ln_carat, edgecolor='k', color='lightblue', bins=20)
plt.title('Histogram of Log-Carat Sizes')
plt.xlabel('Natural Log of Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Count')

plt.show()

Part 7: Scatterplot of Transformed Variables¶

I will create a scatterplot of ln_price against ln_carat, with points colored according to their clarity.

plt.figure(figsize=[8,6])

for i in range(0, len(clarity_levels)):
    plt.scatter(x=diamonds.ln_carat[diamonds.clarity == clarity_levels[i]],
                y=diamonds.ln_price[diamonds.clarity == clarity_levels[i]],

Part 8: Grouping by Cut¶

I will create a grouped DataFrame displaying the mean price and carat size for each cut level.

In [22]:
# create a new DataFrame named gb_cut
# select the cut, price, and carat columns from diamonds
# group the result by cut
# calculate the grouped means
gb_cut = pd.DataFrame(diamonds[['cut','price','carat']].groupby('cut').mean())

# display the resulting DataFrame
gb_cut.head()
Out[22]:

cut

I will now use bar charts to graphically display the information from the DataFrame above.

In [23]:
# create a figure containing two side-by-side bar charts 
# the left chart should display the mean price for each level
# the right chart should display the mean carat size for each level
# # each chart should have a bar for every level of cut

plt.figure(figsize=[12,4])

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.bar(x=gb_cut.index, height=gb_cut['price'], color=cut_pal, edgecolor='black')
plt.xlabel('Cut')
plt.ylabel('Mean Price')
plt.title('Mean Price by Cut')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.bar(x=gb_cut.index, height=gb_cut['carat'], color=cut_pal, edgecolor='black')
plt.xlabel('Cut')
plt.ylabel('Mean Carat Size')
plt.title('Mean Carat Size by Cut')

plt.show()
